====================================================
ETHEREUM
====================================================

====================================================
1. Introduction to Ethereum
====================================================

- Founded in 2015 by Vitalik Buterin.
- A decentralized platform that runs smart contracts.
- Native cryptocurrency: Ether (ETH).
- Key Components:
    • Smart Contracts
    • Gas
    • Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM)
- Supports Decentralized Applications (DApps).

====================================================
2. Enterprise Ethereum Alliance (EEA)
====================================================

- Formed in 2017.
- Consortium of:
    • Technology companies
    • Financial institutions
    • Startups
    • Academics
- Promotes Ethereum technology for enterprise use.
- Focus Areas:
    • Private networks
    • Security
    • Interoperability
    • Standard guidelines
- Example Members:
    • Accenture
    • Intel
    • Microsoft
    • JP Morgan
- Industry Sectors:
    • Healthcare
    • Energy
    • Technology
    • Banking

====================================================
3. Smart Contracts
====================================================

- Self-executing programs stored on Ethereum blockchain.
- Written in Solidity.
- Compiled into bytecode.
- Executed by the Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM).
- Used for:
    • DeFi
    • Tokens
    • Agreements
    • DApps
- Automatically execute when predefined conditions are met.

====================================================
4. Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM)
====================================================

- Runtime environment for smart contracts.
- Stack-based architecture (LIFO).
- Stack size:
    • 1024 elements
    • Each element = 256 bits (32 bytes)
- Ensures deterministic execution across the network.

====================================================
5. Ether (ETH)
====================================================

Ether is the primary digital asset of Ethereum.

- Used as transactional token.
- Facilitates operation of Ethereum network.
- All Gas fees are paid in Ether.

====================================================
6. Bitcoin vs Ethereum
====================================================

BITCOIN                                   ETHEREUM
------------------------------------------------------------------
Uses SHA-256                              Uses Ethash (PoW)*
Used as digital currency                  Used for DApps & Smart Contracts
Competes with FIAT & Gold                 Programmable blockchain
Slower transaction speed                  Faster transaction speed
High mining cost                          Gas-based fee system

*Note: Ethereum moved to Proof of Stake (PoS).

====================================================
7. Gas and Gas Price
====================================================

- Gas measures computational effort.
- Gas Fee = Gas Limit × Gas Price.
- Paid in Ether (ETH).
- Prevents:
    • Network spam
    • Infinite loops
    • Abuse of smart contracts

====================================================
8. Ethereum Accounts
====================================================

Two Types:

1. Externally Owned Account (EOA)
   - Controlled by private key.
   - Can send transactions.
   - Initiates contract creation.

2. Contract Account
   - Controlled by smart contract code.
   - Executes automatically when triggered.

====================================================
9. Ethereum Mining (PoW Concept - Historical)
====================================================

- Process of validating transactions.
- Adding blocks to blockchain.
- Used Proof of Work (PoW) previously.
- Miners received:
    • Block rewards
    • Transaction fees

Uncle Blocks:
- Valid blocks not included in main chain.
- Receive partial reward.

====================================================
10. DAO (Decentralized Autonomous Organization)
====================================================

- Internet-based organization.
- Governed by smart contracts.
- Community voting system.
- No centralized authority.
- Transparent governance model.

====================================================
11. Swarm
====================================================

- Decentralized storage system for Ethereum.
- Content distribution service.
- Uses:
    • Chunking
    • Merkle Trees
- Stores:
    • DApp code
    • Blockchain data
- Peer-to-peer data sharing.

====================================================
12. IPFS (InterPlanetary File System)
====================================================

- Decentralized file storage protocol.
- Uses content addressing (CID).
- Distributed global namespace.
- Frequently integrated with Ethereum DApps.

====================================================
13. BitTorrent
====================================================

- Peer-to-peer file sharing protocol.
- Uses torrent files and trackers.
- Efficient distribution of large files.
- Distributed network architecture.

====================================================
14. Whisper (Decentralized Messaging)
====================================================

- Identity-based messaging protocol.
- Encrypted peer-to-peer communication.
- Low-level decentralized communication API.
- Designed for privacy and anti-tracking.

====================================================
END OF NOTES
====================================================
